[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     79[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe sample case package in Expected Results confirms the shape. The narrative ("Workforce member WF-12849 (registered nurse, cardiology step-down unit) accessed the chart of patient PT-3382091 at 23:47 on May 13, outside the user's documented shift schedule (7 a.m. to 7 p.m. day shift). The user and patient share an uncommon last name (Wojnarowski, name uniqueness 0.81) and the same home ZIP (14620, a small ZIP with approximately 9,400 residents). No care team membership, on-call coverage, encounter assignment, or order signature linking the user to this patient was found. The patient was admitted earlier the same day to a unit other than the user's. The session lasted approximately 90 seconds and included views of demographics, the medication list, and the most recent discharge summary, with no documentation, order entry, or clinical action performed. Recommended for privacy office same-day review.") is explicit content that names both the workforce member's identity, role, department, schedule, and home-ZIP and the patient's identity, sensitivity context, and clinical-evaluation-shaped suggested next steps.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     80[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     81[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe chapter-3-settled discipline (Recipes 3.1, 3.3, 3.4, 3.5, 3.6, 3.7, 3.8) is that high-fanout notification channels carry the alert ID only, and the consuming application fetches the full record by ID through an authenticated path so the notification channel never carries PHI. Recipe 3.9's case event-bus pattern is structurally similar: three subscribers (UI, SIEM, OpenSearch) each fetching from EventBridge. A reader who treats the pseudocode as the implementation specification will produce a system where the full case payload (including the narrative and the workforce-and-patient identity context) flows through the EventBridge bus and into each subscriber's downstream stores and logs.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     82[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     83[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe recipe-3.9 amplification is that the case payload contains both PHI (patient identifier, patient demographics, sensitivity flags, encounter history) and workforce PII (workforce member identifier, role, department, manager, schedule, home ZIP, hire date, employment type) in equal measure. The recipe correctly identifies that workforce PII must be protected with the same discipline as PHI, but the case-bus payload pattern doesn't enforce minimization for either. SIEM systems specifically have substantially broader access scopes than the privacy-office UI; routing the full case payload (with workforce member identity, role, department, home ZIP, and the patient's encounter history) into the SIEM exposes the data to security operations staff who do not have a privacy-office investigation reason.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     84[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     85[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe labor-and-legal dimension is unique to this recipe in the chapter. A workforce member whose case is dismissed-as-legitimate may have had their identity, role, department, manager, schedule, and home ZIP exposed to SIEM operations staff during the routine fanout. Without minimization, this exposure happens for every case (the majority of which are dismissed). For unionized environments and for jurisdictions with employee privacy statutes, this is the architectural discipline that makes the difference between "monitoring with appropriate process" and "monitoring with broader-than-necessary disclosure."[K
