[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    100[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mExpert:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Security / Compliance[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    101[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m "The Technology" Calibration-Subgroup-Performance-And-The-Workforce-Equity-Question subsection ("Track flag rates and confirmed-violation rates by role, department, demographic group, employment type, and shift. Wide variation in flag rates across subgroups warrants investigation: is the variation real (one department genuinely has more curiosity-driven snooping) or artifactual (the baselines are calibrated for one group's workflow and don't fit another's)?"); "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" Equity-And-Subgroup-Performance bullet ("Track flag rates, case-confirmation rates, and adjudication time by role, department, demographic group, employment type, and shift. Wide variation warrants investigation. Consult with employment counsel on disparate-impact considerations before formalizing thresholds that produce different rates across protected categories.").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    102[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    103[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe is unusually clear about subgroup dimensions and the workforce-equity stakes, naming the disparate-impact problem in the explicit framing "do certain roles, certain departments, certain demographic groups get flagged at higher rates than others, and is the difference clinically/operationally justified or is it bias?" The framing-level treatment is the strongest in any chapter-3 recipe on the workforce-equity dimension specifically (which is distinct from the patient-equity dimension addressed in Recipes 3.7 and 3.8).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    104[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    105[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe architectural artifacts that make subgroup monitoring binding rather than aspirational are not specified: where the workforce demographic-and-attribute store lives, who has read access, how it joins to case-state and outcome records, what the audit trail for subgroup queries looks like, what IAM scope the QuickSight dashboard role and the retraining job role need on workforce demographic data, and how the dashboard avoids exposing row-level demographic data to dashboard viewers.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    106[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    107[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe recipe-3.9-distinctive amplification: workforce demographic data has its own legal posture distinct from patient demographic data. Race and ethnicity data on workforce members may be governed by state employment-discrimination statutes (the EEOC's Title VII implementation), by collective-bargaining agreements that restrict secondary use, and by individual-privacy-statute frameworks (Illinois BIPA for biometric data, California's CCPA/CPRA, New York's SHIELD Act). The framing-level treatment is correct; the architectural backstop that operationalizes it is missing. Same finding shape as Recipes 3.2 S2, 3.3 S2, 3.4 S2, 3.5 S2, 3.6 S3, 3.7 S2, 3.8 S2 (now eight chapter-3 recipes deep).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    108[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    109[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add a "Subgroup data access" paragraph or row to Prerequisites: "Workforce-subgroup performance and case-allocation monitoring requires read access to workforce demographic attributes (age band, sex, race, ethnicity, preferred language, employment type, dual-eligibility-equivalent for benefits-and-attribute purposes) and team-level attributes (role, department, shift, training program, manager hierarchy). These attributes may be governed differently from clinical PHI under EEOC/Title VII implementation, state employment-discrimination statutes, collective-bargaining agreements, and individual-privacy-statute frameworks; restrict read access to the workforce-demographic-and-attribute store to the retraining job role and the fairness-monitoring dashboard role, and audit subgroup queries via CloudTrail data events. The QuickSight dashboard backed by Athena should query an aggregated subgroup-metrics table (flag rate by role by department, confirmed-violation rate by demographic group, adjudication time by employment type and shift, case-allocation rate by team), not the raw demographic-joined case archive, so that dashboard-user access does not require row-level read on the subgroup attributes."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    110[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    111[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mStrengthen the IAM row with the per-role scope: retraining job role gets [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mglue:GetTable[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140ms3:GetObject[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m only on the demographic-joined view; fairness-monitoring dashboard role gets read-only on the aggregated subgroup-metrics table. With this finding now flagged across eight chapter-3 recipes, the subgroup-governance appendix is the second-highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment alongside trigger-idempotency.[K
