[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    163[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mBut the BAA-discipline forward reference that Chapter 2's recipes (especially 2.4-2.10) settled is missing. Bedrock with Amazon Titan (or Amazon Nova) foundation models is HIPAA-eligible under the BAA; third-party models on Bedrock (Anthropic Claude, Meta Llama, Cohere, AI21, Mistral) have differing BAA postures and the model's terms of service must be reviewed before PHI-bearing prompts are sent. The recipe's "HIPAA-eligible Bedrock foundation models" phrasing in the TODO doesn't differentiate.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    164[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    165[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mAlso missing: minimum-necessary prompt construction discipline (the case narrative prompt carries the workforce member's identity, role, department, schedule, address ZIP, and the patient's identity, sensitivity flags, encounter history; a naive implementation would carry all of this verbatim); output filtering for policy-violation-determination language (an LLM that says "this user violated the privacy policy" instead of "this access pattern looks more like curiosity than workflow" produces evidentiary problems for the labor-and-legal posture); output filtering for intent-attribution language (an LLM that says "the user intended to access the patient's record for personal reasons" produces problems because intent is what the investigation determines, not what the model asserts); and a full prompt-and-response audit trail tied to the case ID. Same finding shape as Recipes 3.3 V2, 3.4 S4, 3.5 S5, 3.6 S7, 3.7 S5, 3.8 S5.[K
