[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    191[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe correctly identifies the news-and-public-figure-feed integration as policy-driven rather than algorithm-driven and names the right discipline ("the system shouldn't be making judgments about who is 'prominent'; it should be implementing policies set by the privacy office"). But the architectural backstop for this discipline is not specified: which feeds are integrated (commercial news APIs like LexisNexis, Factiva, Meltwater; public-figure databases like Forbes' lists, Wikipedia notable-persons lists; in-house news-monitoring tools), how the feed is filtered against the privacy office's policy (a privacy-office-curated list of name-pattern triggers, or an unfiltered feed with downstream filtering), what the BAA posture of the feed vendor is (most news feeds are not HIPAA-eligible because they are not patient-data systems; the integration must avoid sending patient identifiers to the feed), and what the audit trail for feed-driven scrutiny escalation looks like (every patient flagged via news-feed-match should have the match rationale captured for investigator review).[K
