[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    306[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The Honest Take's "Privileged users are a different program. I cannot stress this enough" lesson; "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" Privileged-user-monitoring bullet ("Database administrators, integration engineers, IT analysts, and researchers have access patterns fundamentally different from clinical workforce. Their monitoring should use different baselines, different feature sets, and different review processes. Some health systems run a separate privileged-access management (PAM) program with session recording, just-in-time access provisioning, and dedicated investigators."); Step 4 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrun_baseline_detector[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (single feature vector with cohort indicator features); Step 6 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcomposite_score[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (single composite-scoring pathway with [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mCOHORT_WEIGHTS_FOR(event.user_role, event.user_department)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m lookup but a single endpoint).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    307[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    308[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe is unusually clear that privileged users are a different program. The Honest Take is unambiguous: "I cannot stress this enough. The detection patterns that work for clinical workforce don't work for IT staff with broad data access. Privileged-user monitoring needs separate baselines, separate detectors (often session recording rather than per-event analysis), separate review workflows, and separate governance." The Why-This-Isn't-Production-Ready bullet reinforces this with the operational reality: "Some health systems run a separate privileged-access management (PAM) program with session recording, just-in-time access provisioning, and dedicated investigators. The detection patterns described in this recipe apply less directly to this population."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    309[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    310[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe closing recommendation is direct: "If you're building a single system that tries to monitor both populations with the same detector, you're going to either flood the queue with privileged-user noise or miss real privileged-user incidents. Build them as related but distinct."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    311[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    312[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mStep 4's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrun_baseline_detector[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m correctly implements per-cohort behavioral baselines ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mpeer_group_id = derive_peer_group(event.user_role, event.user_department, user_baseline.shift_pattern)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m) and Step 6's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcomposite_score[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m correctly implements per-cohort weights ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mweights = COHORT_WEIGHTS_FOR(event.user_role, event.user_department)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m). But the detector pipeline is a single pipeline; privileged-user events flow through the same rules engine, the same baseline detector, the same graph detector, the same sequence model, the same composite scoring, and into the same case queue as clinical-workforce events. Cohort-stratified weights and thresholds modulate the scoring but don't separate the workflow.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    313[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    314[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mTwo specific architectural primitives that distinguish privileged-user-separate-program from privileged-user-cohort-features:[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    315[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    316[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m1[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mSession recording for privileged users.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The Honest Take explicitly names "session recording rather than per-event analysis" as the right detection paradigm for privileged users. Per-event audit-log analysis catches "this DBA accessed this patient's record" but misses "what queries did the DBA run against the database during this access window." Session recording (via PAM tooling integrated with database proxies and SSH bastions) captures the query content, which is the right grain for privileged-user detection.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    317[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    318[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m2[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mSeparate case queue and review workflow.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Privileged-user investigations require deeper technical context (database query patterns, infrastructure access patterns, integration-engine activity logs) that the clinical-workforce privacy-office investigators may not have the expertise to evaluate. A separate case queue staffed by infrastructure-security analysts produces better outcomes than mixing the populations.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    319[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    320[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mA reader who treats the pseudocode as the implementation specification produces a system that exhibits exactly the failure mode the prose warns against: a single-detector, single-queue architecture that floods the queue with privileged-user noise (because their broad-access patterns produce high deviation scores against any baseline) or misses real privileged-user incidents (because the detection patterns optimized for clinical workforce don't catch the methodical privileged-user extraction case).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    321[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    322[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mSame prose-vs-pseudocode asymmetry pattern as Recipes 3.4 A3, 3.5 A3-A4, 3.6 A3, 3.7 A3-A4, 3.8 A3-A5-A7.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    323[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    324[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Update the General Architecture Pattern section to name privileged-user separation as a first-class architectural concern: "Privileged-user populations (database administrators, integration engineers, IT analysts, researchers, and other workforce members with bulk-data access) require a distinct detection pipeline. Per-event audit-log analysis catches some patterns, but the operationally-correct approach uses session recording (via PAM tooling integrated with database proxies and SSH bastions), bulk-export-and-query monitoring, and longer-time-scale behavioral analysis. The case queue for privileged-user investigations is staffed by infrastructure-security analysts rather than the privacy-office team that handles clinical-workforce cases. The privileged-user pipeline shares the relationship graph and the case-management infrastructure with the clinical-workforce pipeline but uses separate detectors, separate baselines, separate thresholds, and separate review workflows."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    325[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    326[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mAdd a paragraph to the AWS Implementation section naming the AWS-side primitives for privileged-user separation: "PAM-integrated session recording can flow through Amazon CloudWatch Logs (with KMS encryption and customer-managed retention) or AWS Database Activity Streams for RDS. The privileged-user case queue is a separate AppSync/API Gateway endpoint with separate IAM scopes for the infrastructure-security analyst role. The composite-scoring Lambda dispatches to per-population scoring services: [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mclinical-anomaly-model[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m for clinical-workforce events, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mprivileged-user-anomaly-model[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m for privileged-user events. Both populations share the relationship graph and the case-management database but the case queues are separate."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    327[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    328[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mCross-reference in The Honest Take's "Privileged users are a different program" lesson: "The architecture supports privileged-user separation as a first-class concern (separate detection pipeline, separate case queue, separate review workflow); the pilot can start with clinical-workforce only and add privileged-user as a parallel program when the PAM tooling and the infrastructure-security review function are in place."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    329[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    330[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m####[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mFinding A4: Service-Account Inventory Named in Why-This-Isn't-Production-Ready but Not Architecturally Enforced[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    331[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    332[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mSeverity:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m MEDIUM[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    333[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mExpert:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Architecture / Pedagogy[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    334[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" Service-account-and-integration-account-inventory bullet ("Service accounts, integration accounts, and shared accounts must be inventoried and modeled separately from human users. Many programs discover unexpected service accounts during inventory, some with overly broad permissions. The inventory itself produces actionable findings before the detection pipeline does."); "Where it struggles" Service-accounts-and-integration-accounts paragraph ("Service-account behavior must be modeled separately from human-user behavior; conflating them either floods the queue with service-account 'anomalies' or lets human anomalies hide in service-account noise"); Step 1 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mon_ehr_audit_event[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (workforce_id resolution); Step 4 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrun_baseline_detector[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m (per-user behavioral baselines).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    335[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    336[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe is unusually clear about service-account inventory as a precondition to deployment and as an operational discipline. The Why-This-Isn't-Production-Ready bullet is unambiguous: "Service accounts, integration accounts, and shared accounts must be inventoried and modeled separately from human users." The Where-it-struggles paragraph reinforces: "Service-account behavior must be modeled separately from human-user behavior; conflating them either floods the queue with service-account 'anomalies' or lets human anomalies hide in service-account noise."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    337[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    338[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mStep 1's workforce_id resolution and Step 4's per-user behavioral baselines do not architecturally distinguish service accounts from human users. A service account that has access to many patient records (a typical pattern for an EHR-to-data-warehouse integration account, an EHR-to-analytics-platform account, or a clinical-decision-support service account) appears as a single workforce_id with extremely high access volume, extremely high unique-patient count, and extremely consistent off-hours access patterns. Against a peer-group baseline of human clinical workforce, the service account looks like an extreme anomaly on every dimension.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    339[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    340[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mTwo specific architectural primitives that distinguish service-account-inventory-and-modeling from service-account-as-just-another-user:[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    341[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    342[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m1[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mAccount-class enrichment.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The workforce-identity DynamoDB table should carry an [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140maccount_class[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m attribute ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mhuman_clinical[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mhuman_administrative[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mhuman_privileged[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mservice_integration[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mservice_analytics[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mservice_clinical_decision_support[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mshared_kiosk[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140munknown[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m) populated from the IAM-and-HRIS source-of-truth. The enrichment layer attaches the account class to every event; the detector dispatches to account-class-specific detection logic.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    343[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    344[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m2[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mService-account-specific detection patterns.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Service accounts have characteristic patterns that don't apply to humans: access patterns aligned with scheduled batch windows; access to records that map to a documented integration scope; data-access volume bounded by the integration's documented purpose. The detection logic for service accounts is "deviation from documented integration scope" rather than "deviation from peer-group baseline."[K
