[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    624[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The sample narrative is well-constructed and demonstrates the constraint boundary the recipe correctly establishes (decision support, not decision-making; no policy-violation determinations, no intent attributions). The narrative cites features ("session lasted approximately 90 seconds and included views of demographics, the medication list, and the most recent discharge summary"), notes the absence of clinical-workflow indicators ("no documentation, order entry, or clinical action performed"), and closes with a recommendation phrase ("Recommended for privacy office same-day review") that sits squarely in decision-support territory. This is largely the right model output discipline.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    625[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    626[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mBut the closing phrase ("Recommended for privacy office same-day review") is operating-decision-shaped rather than narrative-shaped; it's a tier-assignment recommendation rather than a pattern description. The tier assignment is properly the output of the calibration-and-tier-mapping layer (Step 6), not of the LLM narrative (Step 7). A narrative that says "Recommended for tier-1 review" effectively is making a workflow-routing decision; the LLM's output should describe the access pattern and let the calibration-and-tier-mapping layer make the routing decision based on the composite score.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    627[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
